images.caption: Morgan William's jumper at the buzzer ended UConn's winning streak at 111 games in one of the biggest upsets in women's NCAA tournament history.

related.description: UConn hadn't lost since November 2014, winning an NCAA-record 111 straight games that included two NCAA titles and a 38-0 season in 2015-16. Mississippi State snapped the historic run Friday.

article.headline: UConn women roll past Cincinnati to pick up 98th straight win

images.name: Great wraparound pass from Williams sets up Collier to score
images.caption: Gabby Williams grabs a board, then whips a great pass to Napheesa Collier who scores.

article.linkText: UConn women top Cincy for 98th straight win
article.story:
CINCINNATI -- For top-ranked UConn, there's no avoiding the very big number anymore.

The Huskies rolled to a 96-49 victory over Cincinnati on Tuesday night, behind Napheesa Collier's perfect shooting, and that leaves them within arm's reach of the NCAA's first triple-digit win streak.

Two more wins, and it'll be 100 in a row.

"The last thing on my mind is the number," coach Geno Auriemma said. "I'm sure with this weekend coming up, it will be a big topic of conversation. Right now, we just needed a game like this, where we did a lot of things really, really well."

Nobody was better than Collier, who made all 10 of her shots -- including one from beyond the arc -- and all three of her free throws for 24 points. She also had 12 rebounds, six assists and five blocked shots.

"It's not really too much of a surprise for us because she does that every day in practice every day," said Katie Lou Samuelson, who added 20 points. "She's all over the place, and it's something you just kind of come to expect from her."

Well, one of the Huskies was taken aback by the 10-for-10.

"I didn't know until after the game," Collier said. "I was really surprised by that."

There was no surprise in how UConn's 98th straight win unfolded. The Huskies (23-0, 11-0 American Athletic) made quick work of former UConn star Jamelle Elliott's team, pulling ahead 49-22 at halftime with three players already in double figures. Shanice Johnson led Cincinnati with 20 points.

The Huskies improved to 17-0 all time against Cincinnati (14-9, 5-5), led by their former star and assistant coach. Elliott remains close friends with Auriemma. They go out to dinner the night before their annual games and talk about everything except what's coming up.

Elliott noted that UConn wasn't expected to be so dominant this season.

"I heard it all the time," she said. "I got sick of hearing it. I am an alum. I'm a proud alum. And I still root for them every game that they play outside of ours."

The Huskies already had the Division I women's record, with 35 straight road wins. Their 36th on Tuesday surpassed Phog Allen's mark with Kansas in 1924-28.

Of course, the biggest number is now just ahead.

"We don't pay attention to the streak in the sense that we want to get to a certain number," Collier said. "We just don't want to lose."

MOPPING UP

The Huskies have won 106 straight road games against unranked teams since a loss at Arizona State on Dec. 21, 2004.

DANGERFIELD COMING AROUND

Point guard Crystal Dangerfield had five points, five assists and one steal in 19 minutes. She's still getting back in form after missing five games with a foot injury. She has played in the past three, and Auriemma hopes she's close to form for the game Monday against No. 6 South Carolina.

"Little by little, it will come back," Auriemma said. "It better come back before Monday night -- or else."

SAMUELSON OFF

Samuelson went 3-of-11 from beyond the arc, part of a two-game slump. She's 3-for-18 on 3-point attempts in the past two games.

"The last game, it didn't feel very good," Samuelson said. "Today it felt good, but they just didn't go in."

BIG PICTURE

UConn: While the Huskies close in on 100 wins, Auriemma passed C. Vivian Stringer of Rutgers for fourth on the career wins list, with 978.

Cincinnati: The Bearcats' past six losses against UConn have been by 65, 60, 59, 62, 54 and 47 points.

UP NEXT

The Huskies continue their pursuit of No. 100 when they host SMU on Saturday. They could reach the mark against South Carolina on Monday at Gampel Pavilion.

The Bearcats play at Houston on Saturday. They beat the Cougars 85-64 on Jan. 7 at home, part of a five-game win streak.
